# `Dregg2.Crypto.MlDsaVerifyReal` — the REAL ML-DSA-65 `verify_internal` (FIPS 204), as EXECUTABLE `def`s.

BRICK 6, the KEYSTONE: it assembles the five landed, KAT- and crate-gated bricks into the actual FIPS 204
verify, replacing the `A = id` scalar caricature of `Fips204Verify.lean` with the full-dimension ML-DSA-65
verification relation. Nothing here is reimplemented — every primitive is REUSED:

* SHAKE-256 — `Dregg2.Crypto.Keccak` (BRICK 1, byte-exact KAT).
* `R_q` ring + `ntt`/`intt`/`pointwiseMul`/`addPoly`/`subPoly` — `Dregg2.Crypto.MlDsaRing` (BRICK 2, the fast
  transform proven equal to the negacyclic product).
* `sampleInBall` — `Dregg2.Crypto.MlDsaSampleInBall` (BRICK 3, exact `τ = 49` weight).
* `expandA` (NTT-domain `Â`, `6×5`) — `Dregg2.Crypto.MlDsaExpandA` (BRICK 4).
* `pkDecode` / `sigDecode` / `packBits` — `Dregg2.Crypto.MlDsaCodec` (BRICK 5, round-trips REAL crate bytes).

## The verify (FIPS 204 Algorithm 8 `verify_internal`, wrapped by Algorithm 3 for the `ctx` framing)

`(ρ, t1) := pkDecode pk`; `(c̃, z, h) := sigDecode sig` (a rejected hint yields `h.size ≠ 6` → fail-closed).
`Â := expandA ρ`. `tr := SHAKE256(pk, 64)`; `M' := 0x00 ‖ |ctx| ‖ ctx ‖ M`; `μ := SHAKE256(tr ‖ M', 64)`.
`ĉ := ntt (sampleInBall c̃)`. Per row `i`: `Az_i := Σ_j Â[i·5+j] ⊙ ntt(z_j)`,
`ct1_i := ĉ ⊙ ntt(2^d · t1_i)`, `w_i := intt(Az_i − ct1_i)` — the `w'Approx = A·z − c·t1·2^d`. Then
`w1'_i := UseHint(h_i, w_i)` componentwise, `c̃' := SHAKE256(μ ‖ w1Encode(w1'), 48)`, and the verdict is
`(c̃' = c̃) ∧ (‖z‖∞ < γ₁−β = 524092)`.

## `UseHint` / `Decompose` — FIPS 204 Algorithms 36 & 40, at the ML-DSA-65 numbers

`q = 8380417`, `γ₂ = (q−1)/32 = 261888`, `α = 2γ₂ = 523776`, `m = (q−1)/(2γ₂) = 16`. `Decompose(r)` centers
the low part `r0 = r mod± α ∈ (−γ₂, γ₂]` and returns `(r1, r0)` with the `r − r0 = q−1` special case folding
`r1` to `0`; so `HighBits(r) = r1 ∈ [0, 16)`. `UseHint(h, r)` carries `r1 ± 1 (mod 16)` on `h = 1`
(sign by `r0`), else `r1`. `w1Encode` is `SimpleBitPack` of the 6 `w1'` polys at `bitlen(15) = 4` bits/coeff
(reusing the codec's `packBits`), hence `μ ‖ 768 bytes`.

## PROVENANCE OF THE VECTORS IN *THIS* FILE: CRATE-GENERATED, NOT NIST

`genPk` / `genSig` / `genSigTampered` below are `fips204` v0.4.6 CRATE output. On them the CRATE, not
FIPS 204, is the specification anchor. That is a real limit and it is why `verify_accepts_real` is named
for the crate signature it accepts and not for a standard.

The NIST-published anchor for this same `verifyCore` lives in `Dregg2.Crypto.MlDsaSigVerAcvp`:
`verifyCore_matches_acvp_sigVer` runs `verifyCore` over the COMPLETE NIST ACVP `ML-DSA-sigVer-FIPS204`
ML-DSA-65 external/pure group (`tgId = 3`, `tcId` 31–45 — 3 expected-accept, 12 expected-reject) and
proves it reproduces NIST's own `testPassed` verdict on every case. That module cites the exact
ACVP-Server file, group, test-case ids and downloaded-file digests. Read the two together: the gate below
is crate agreement, `MlDsaSigVerAcvp` is the NIST anchor. Neither is a `forall` — that is `VerifyCoreEqSpec`.

## THE ANTI-FAKE GATE — accept a REAL crate signature, reject tampers

`genPk`/`genSig`/`genSigTampered` are a genuine ML-DSA-65 keypair+signature from the real `fips204` v0.4.6
crate (`ml_dsa_65::try_keygen` + `.try_sign(msg, ctx)`) over `msg = b"dregg real verify KAT"`, `ctx = ε`,
pinned verbatim. The crate's OWN `pk.verify` was checked in the generator: `true` on the genuine signature,
`false` on the one-byte-flipped `genSigTampered`, `false` on the wrong message. The gate makes Lean's verify
AGREE with the crate's bool:

* `verify_accepts_real` (a `native_decide` theorem) — `verifyCore genPk genMsg [] genSig = true` (Lean
  ACCEPTS the genuine crate signature).
* `#guard verifyCore genPk genMsg [] genSigTampered == false` (Lean REJECTS the one-byte tamper).
* `#guard verifyCore genPk (genMsg ++ [0]) [] genSig == false` (Lean REJECTS the wrong message).

`native_decide` / `#guard` run the COMPILED `def`s. If the `μ` framing, the centered-`Decompose`, the
`w1Encode` width, or the `2^d` NTT scaling were wrong, `verify_accepts_real` would NOT close on the real
signature. No `sorry`, no user `axiom`, no toy substitute.

## RESIDUAL

`verify_accepts_real`, the one remaining `native_decide` theorem here (kept because
`verifyCore_eq_challengeMatches_and_norm_witness` in `VerifyCoreEqSpec` consumes it as a proof term), has trusted base the
per-declaration `native_decide` compiler-trust axiom `verify_accepts_real._native.native_decide.ax`
(the v4.30 realization of `Lean.ofReduceBool` / `Lean.trustCompiler`, i.e. compiled evaluation) — the
SAME residual `Keccak`, `MlDsaRing`, and `MlDsaCodec` already name. The `#guard` reject/length vectors are commands with no
proof term and add NO axiom.
